\begin_layout Standard
We assume that carbon enters the system at a constant rate through litter-fall,
 and that carbon exits the system by respiration and humification, also
 at constant rates.
 We also assume that the model starts out with zero litter (and thus zero
 carbon).
 This assumption seems reasonable, since it simulates forest rejuvenation
 after a ground fire.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our objective, then, is to model the amount of carbon contained in the litter
 at any point in time.
 In mathematical terms, we seek to compute 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 at any point in time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

, given the constant rate of litter-fall 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, the constant rate of respiration 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

, and the constant rate of humification 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

, within the system.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We've chosen to represent the model as a differential equation,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x'(t)=z-x(t)*(r+h)\label{eq:simple_diff_eq}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We now also assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $r=h$
\end_inset

, meaning that the rates of respiration and humifcation are equal.
 Thus, we can combine them into a single rate 
\begin_inset Formula $k=r+h$
\end_inset

.
 Updating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:simple_diff_eq"

\end_inset

, we have
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x'(t)=z-k*x(t)\label{eq:simple_diff_eq_simplified}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Solution to the Simple Litter Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The general solution to the differential equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:simple_diff_eq_simplified"

\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x(t)=c_{1}e^{-kt}+\frac{z}{k}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To find a specific solution to the differential equation, we rely on the
 assumption that there is initially zero carbon in the system: 
\begin_inset Formula $x(0)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, we can find 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
x(0) & = & c_{1}e^{-k0}+\frac{z}{k}\\
\implies c_{1} & = & -\frac{z}{k}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
A Concrete Solution to the Simple Litter Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the existing literature, we can estimate parameter values to represent
 real-world measurements of a temperate forest.
 We let
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
z & = & 240\; g\; C/m^{2}\\
k=r+h & = & 0.4/year
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Plugging these parameter values into the model equations, we find
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
c_{1} & = & -\frac{z}{k}\\
 & = & -\frac{240}{0.4}\\
 & = & -600
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
And equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:simple_diff_eq_simplified"

\end_inset

 becomes
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x(t)=600-600e^{-0.4t}\label{eq:simple_specific_solution_temperate_forest}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

