\begin_layout Subsection
Analysis of the Simple Litter Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:plot_of_solution_to_simple_litter_model"

\end_inset

, it appears that the model achieves equilibrium at 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)=600$
\end_inset

.
 We can validate this observation by finding the fixed points of the model.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
By definition, the fixed point of our model exists when 
\begin_inset Formula $x'(t)=0$
\end_inset

, which occurs only when 
\begin_inset Formula $-600=-600e^{-0.4t}$
\end_inset

.
 Since this equation does not have any real roots, we can't analytically
 find a fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

 for any sensible measure of time (time can't be measured with a complex
 number), but we can approximate it numerically.
 Indeed by 
\begin_inset Formula $t=12$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 is within 1% of the equilibrium value 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)=600$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Working with the assumption that there exists a fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $t^{*}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t^{*})=600$
\end_inset

, we can use graphical stability analysis to determine the stability of
 the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t^{*})$
\end_inset

.
 Here we see a plot of 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 versus 
\begin_inset Formula $x'(t)$
\end_inset

, annotated with the usual markings used in graphical stability analysis
\end_layout

